---
import TheLeagueLayout from '../../layouts/TheLeagueLayout.astro';

export const prerender = true;
---

<TheLeagueLayout title="About This Project | The League">
  <main class="about-page">

    <!-- ===== HERO ===== -->
    <header class="about-hero">
      <div class="about-hero__eyebrow">
        <span class="about-tag">Production Case Study</span>
        <span class="about-dot">·</span>
        <span class="about-hero__date">2025 – Present</span>
      </div>

      <h1 class="about-hero__title">Most AI experiments live in notebooks.<br>This one lives in production.</h1>

      <p class="about-hero__deck">
        A full-stack dynasty fantasy football platform built from scratch as a sandbox
        for human-AI collaboration. Not a demo. Not a prototype. A system that 16
        league members use every week to make decisions worth real fantasy money, built with
        explicit architectural separations between what machines should own and what
        they should assist with.
      </p>

      <div class="about-hero__stack">
        <span class="about-stack-item">Astro + TypeScript</span>
        <span class="about-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="about-stack-item">MFL API Integration</span>
        <span class="about-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="about-stack-item">Claude API</span>
        <span class="about-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="about-stack-item">Structured AI Scaffolding</span>
        <span class="about-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="about-stack-item">Dynasty Contract Engine</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- ===== STATS STRIP ===== -->
    <div class="about-stats">
      <div class="about-stats__item">
        <div class="about-stats__value">15+</div>
        <div class="about-stats__label">Years of salary history ingested</div>
      </div>
      <div class="about-stats__item">
        <div class="about-stats__value">$45M</div>
        <div class="about-stats__label">Salary cap — exact, enforced, tested</div>
      </div>
      <div class="about-stats__item">
        <div class="about-stats__value">2</div>
        <div class="about-stats__label">Leagues on one codebase</div>
      </div>
      <div class="about-stats__item">
        <div class="about-stats__value">0</div>
        <div class="about-stats__label">AI calls in the deterministic layer</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="about-body">

      <!-- ===== 01: THE PROBLEM DOMAIN ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">01</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">The Problem Domain</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">Why dynasty fantasy football is a well-formed substrate for AI research</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-two-col">
          <div class="about-prose">
            <p>
              Dynasty fantasy football isn't the same game most people know. You don't redraft
              every year. You own players across multiple seasons, sign them to multi-year contracts,
              manage a salary cap, and plan roster construction the way an NFL front office would —
              except you're doing it in a league chat at 11pm on a Tuesday, which is its own
              kind of decision-making environment.
            </p>
            <p>
              The domain turns out to be an unusually well-formed substrate for exploring AI
              integration because it combines two kinds of problems that require fundamentally
              different tools: <strong>hard-constraint satisfaction</strong> and <strong>probabilistic estimation</strong>.
            </p>
            <p>
              The salary cap is $45M. Not approximately. Not "around." Violating it disqualifies
              your roster. That constraint is not a place for probabilistic reasoning — it's a
              function. Meanwhile, figuring out whether a 27-year-old running back is worth a
              3-year, $9M contract requires reasoning across injury history, usage trends,
              offensive scheme, age curves, and roster context simultaneously. That is exactly
              where structured AI reasoning adds value.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="about-domain-box">
            <div class="about-domain-type">
              <div class="about-domain-type__label">Hard Constraints</div>
              <div class="about-domain-type__items">
                <div class="about-domain-item">Salary cap: exactly $45,000,000</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">Roster limit: exactly 28 players</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">Contract escalation: exactly 10%/yr</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">Franchise tag rules: explicitly defined</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-domain-type__verdict about-domain-type__verdict--det">Functions. Tests. No AI.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-domain-type about-domain-type--prob">
              <div class="about-domain-type__label">Probabilistic Signals</div>
              <div class="about-domain-type__items">
                <div class="about-domain-item">Player age &amp; durability curves</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">Trade value relative to market</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">Auction clearing price prediction</div>
                <div class="about-domain-item">Free agent fit by roster context</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-domain-type__verdict about-domain-type__verdict--prob">Estimates. Scaffolded AI. Evaluated.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 02: ARCHITECTURE ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">02</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">Architecture: The Separation</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">The core design decision that made everything else possible</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            The core architectural decision was made early and never compromised: deterministic
            logic and probabilistic reasoning are separated at the interface level, not just
            organizationally. This sounds obvious. In practice, it requires constant discipline —
            especially as features compound and the temptation to "just let the model handle it"
            grows.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-arch">
          <div class="about-arch__layer about-arch__layer--det">
            <div class="about-arch__layer-header">
              <span class="about-arch__layer-title">Deterministic Layer</span>
              <span class="about-arch__layer-badge">TypeScript · Fully Tested</span>
            </div>
            <div class="about-arch__modules">
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Salary Engine</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc"><code>salary-calculations.ts</code> — cap math, escalation, dead money</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">MFL API Layer</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Typed wrappers around third-party API quirks; normalized data contracts</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Contract Logic</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Franchise tag rules, contract expiry, cap hold calculations</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Year Rollover</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Date-aware league/season year resolution; testable via <code>?testDate=</code></div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-arch__bridge">
            <div class="about-arch__bridge-label">Typed Context Window</div>
            <div class="about-arch__bridge-desc">
              Structured, verified data flows upward. The probabilistic layer receives facts, not raw API responses.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-arch__layer about-arch__layer--prob">
            <div class="about-arch__layer-header">
              <span class="about-arch__layer-title">Probabilistic Layer</span>
              <span class="about-arch__layer-badge">Claude API · Scaffolded · Evaluated</span>
            </div>
            <div class="about-arch__modules">
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Trade Analysis</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Value framing, relative surplus analysis, contextual reasoning</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Auction Predictor</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Historical signal + roster context + scarcity → clearing price estimate</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Free Agent Fit</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Positional need scoring + roster construction heuristics</div>
              </div>
              <div class="about-arch__module">
                <div class="about-arch__module-name">Decision Support</div>
                <div class="about-arch__module-desc">Summarization, option framing, risk surface identification</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <blockquote class="about-quote">
          "A model touching salary cap calculations would be a regression, not an enhancement.
          The question isn't whether AI is powerful enough — it's whether this is the right
          kind of question to route through a probabilistic system."
        </blockquote>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 03: AI SCAFFOLDING ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">03</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">The Scaffolding Pattern</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">Structured interfaces around AI, not chatbot wrappers</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            Every AI-assisted feature follows the same four-component scaffolding pattern.
            The goal is to make AI behavior <em>predictable</em>, <em>traceable</em>, and
            <em>improvable</em> — which requires more upfront structure than most teams invest in.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-scaffold">
          <div class="about-scaffold__item">
            <div class="about-scaffold__num">1</div>
            <div class="about-scaffold__content">
              <div class="about-scaffold__title">Structured Context Window</div>
              <div class="about-scaffold__body">
                Each AI call receives a typed, scoped subset of league data relevant to the
                specific question. Not "here's everything" — a curated context that includes
                the roster, cap situation, historical data points, and constraints applicable
                to this decision. The context window is a product decision, not an
                implementation detail.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-scaffold__item">
            <div class="about-scaffold__num">2</div>
            <div class="about-scaffold__content">
              <div class="about-scaffold__title">Typed Prompt Templates</div>
              <div class="about-scaffold__body">
                Prompts are structured templates with explicit output format specifications,
                reasoning requirements, and constraint declarations. "Given this player's
                contract, age, and recent performance, rate their trade value 1–10 and
                explain the top three factors" produces auditable output. "Analyze this
                player" produces noise.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-scaffold__item">
            <div class="about-scaffold__num">3</div>
            <div class="about-scaffold__content">
              <div class="about-scaffold__title">Pre-Deployment Failure Catalog</div>
              <div class="about-scaffold__body">
                Before any AI feature ships, its failure modes are documented: What does
                confidently wrong output look like for this feature? What signals indicate
                the model is hallucinating? What's the graceful fallback? The failure catalog
                directly informs the evaluation rubric, which means you're testing for
                failure modes you've already characterized rather than discovering them in production.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-scaffold__item">
            <div class="about-scaffold__num">4</div>
            <div class="about-scaffold__content">
              <div class="about-scaffold__title">Traceable Outputs</div>
              <div class="about-scaffold__body">
                Every AI-assisted inference displays the source data it reasoned from.
                A trade recommendation shows the salary comparison. An auction estimate
                shows the historical comps. Users can inspect the reasoning chain and
                identify when the model's inputs were wrong — which is usually more
                actionable than identifying when its reasoning was wrong.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 04: THE META-SYSTEM ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">04</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">The Meta-System</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">AI as a development collaborator, not just a product feature</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-two-col about-two-col--wide-text">
          <div class="about-prose">
            <p>
              The most technically interesting aspect of this project is not any individual feature.
              It's the development workflow itself — a structured AI collaboration system built into
              the development process rather than bolted onto the product.
            </p>
            <p>
              The <strong>AI Insights System</strong> is a structured corpus of domain knowledge
              organized into files by domain (frontend patterns, API quirks, design system tokens,
              accessibility rules) and by feature (each major feature has its own learnings file).
              This corpus is loaded into the AI's context at the start of every development task.
              After each task, new learnings are written back.
            </p>
            <p>
              This creates a feedback loop between the AI's behavior and a maintained knowledge
              base — essentially prompt-engineering at the organizational level rather than the
              single-call level. The AI's knowledge of the codebase compounds across sessions
              rather than resetting.
            </p>
            <p>
              The same principles that govern product AI scaffolding govern this system: scoped
              context, structured format, explicit update criteria, and failure modes that get
              caught and corrected rather than silently accumulated.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="about-insights-viz">
            <div class="about-insights-header">AI Insights System</div>
            <div class="about-insights-flow">
              <div class="about-insights-node about-insights-node--trigger">
                Task begins
              </div>
              <div class="about-insights-arrow">↓</div>
              <div class="about-insights-node about-insights-node--load">
                Load relevant domain + feature files into context
              </div>
              <div class="about-insights-arrow">↓</div>
              <div class="about-insights-node about-insights-node--work">
                AI executes task with accumulated project knowledge
              </div>
              <div class="about-insights-arrow">↓</div>
              <div class="about-insights-node about-insights-node--write">
                New learnings written back to corpus
              </div>
              <div class="about-insights-arrow about-insights-arrow--loop">↑ compounds</div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-insights-files">
              <div class="about-insights-file">domains/design-system.md</div>
              <div class="about-insights-file">domains/mfl-api.md</div>
              <div class="about-insights-file">domains/frontend.md</div>
              <div class="about-insights-file">features/trade-builder.md</div>
              <div class="about-insights-file">features/auction-predictor.md</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <blockquote class="about-quote">
          "The AI Insights System is itself a demonstration of the same principles applied to
          the product: structured context, explicit formats, and a maintained feedback loop.
          The development workflow is the feature."
        </blockquote>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 05: RELIABILITY ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">05</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">Reliability by Design</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">What production deployment teaches you about AI systems that notebooks don't</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            Two reliability patterns emerged that only become visible in production — after a
            full season of real decisions, real feedback, and real consequences when outputs
            were wrong.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-reliability-grid">
          <div class="about-reliability-card">
            <div class="about-reliability-card__eyebrow">Pattern 01</div>
            <div class="about-reliability-card__title">Bounded Inference Outperforms Open-Ended Analysis</div>
            <div class="about-reliability-card__body">
              <p>
                Scoped questions produce more useful outputs than open-ended ones — not
                because the model is more capable with constraints, but because constraints
                make failure modes smaller and more observable. "Rate this player's trade
                value 1–10 and explain the top three factors" produces output where the
                failure is detectable: you can check whether the three factors are the
                right ones. "Analyze this player" produces output where failure is invisible
                until it matters.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-reliability-card">
            <div class="about-reliability-card__eyebrow">Pattern 02</div>
            <div class="about-reliability-card__title">Inputs Are More Likely Wrong Than Reasoning</div>
            <div class="about-reliability-card__body">
              <p>
                When AI-assisted outputs are wrong, the root cause is almost always
                wrong inputs — stale data, an off-by-one in salary calculations, a
                player whose NFL team changed mid-season. The model's reasoning, given
                correct inputs, is usually fine. This shifts the reliability investment:
                the deterministic layer's accuracy directly determines the quality of
                AI outputs, which means testing the data pipeline is as important as
                evaluating the model.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 06: ITERATION ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">06</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">Iteration as a System Property</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">How the development model mirrors the AI integration philosophy</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            The same principles that govern AI scaffolding govern the development process:
            reduce ambiguity upfront, design for resilience, ship small and observe, close
            feedback loops. Every feature is a composable component of a larger system rather
            than a standalone deliverable.
          </p>
          <p>
            The What's New system — an editorial changelog with a consistent voice, screenshot
            requirements, and a weekly rollup — is not documentation overhead. It's a
            forcing function. Writing "what changed and why it matters" in plain English requires
            understanding what actually changed. If you can't explain it, you haven't finished
            thinking about it.
          </p>
          <p>
            The entire architecture — every utility, every data structure, every API wrapper —
            is designed with the Auction Price Predictor in mind as the culminating feature.
            This means features aren't shipped when they work in isolation. They're shipped
            when they contribute to a system that can eventually support probabilistic auction
            valuation at the position-scarcity level. Composability is a first-class requirement.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-timeline">
          <div class="about-timeline__phase">
            <div class="about-timeline__label">Foundation</div>
            <div class="about-timeline__items">
              <span class="about-tl-item">MFL API integration</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Salary engine</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Roster hub</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Contract logic</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-timeline__arrow">→</div>
          <div class="about-timeline__phase">
            <div class="about-timeline__label">Decision Tools</div>
            <div class="about-timeline__items">
              <span class="about-tl-item">Trade builder</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Free agent view</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">League planner</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Draft predictor</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-timeline__arrow">→</div>
          <div class="about-timeline__phase">
            <div class="about-timeline__label">Analytics Layer</div>
            <div class="about-timeline__items">
              <span class="about-tl-item">Salary MVPs</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Dead money</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">League summary</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Historical analysis</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-timeline__arrow">→</div>
          <div class="about-timeline__phase about-timeline__phase--next">
            <div class="about-timeline__label">Predictive System</div>
            <div class="about-timeline__items">
              <span class="about-tl-item">Auction predictor</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">AI trade framing</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Value signals</span>
              <span class="about-tl-item">Scarcity model</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 07: WHATS NEXT ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">07</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">The Auction Price Predictor</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">What this entire system was designed to support</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            Dynasty auction drafts are a hard prediction problem. You're not just estimating
            player value — you're estimating clearing price, which is a function of player
            quality, positional scarcity relative to the remaining pool, budget distributions
            across 12 competing managers, and information asymmetry. The same player goes for
            dramatically different prices depending on when in the auction they're nominated,
            how many similar players remain available, and whether the managers with the
            most budget have already filled their need at that position.
          </p>
          <p>
            This is precisely the right problem for structured AI reasoning — layered on top
            of a deterministic foundation that knows exactly how much cap room each team has,
            exactly which positions remain unfilled, and exactly what each player's historical
            salary trajectory looks like.
          </p>
          <p>
            Every technical decision made in this project — the separation of layers, the typed
            context windows, the composable utilities, the historical data ingestion — was made
            with this system in mind. The foundation is solid. The predictor is what comes next.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-predictor-box">
          <div class="about-predictor-box__title">Auction Predictor: System Inputs</div>
          <div class="about-predictor-box__grid">
            <div class="about-predictor-input">
              <div class="about-predictor-input__label">Historical Salary Data</div>
              <div class="about-predictor-input__desc">15 years of auction results, normalized by year and position</div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-predictor-input">
              <div class="about-predictor-input__label">Roster Context</div>
              <div class="about-predictor-input__desc">Real-time cap room and position gaps per team, deterministically calculated</div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-predictor-input">
              <div class="about-predictor-input__label">Positional Scarcity</div>
              <div class="about-predictor-input__desc">Pool depth at each position, tiered by projected value</div>
            </div>
            <div class="about-predictor-input">
              <div class="about-predictor-input__label">Player Signal</div>
              <div class="about-predictor-input__desc">Age, contract status, performance trajectory, NFL context</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="about-predictor-box__output">
            <span class="about-predictor-box__output-label">Output →</span>
            <span class="about-predictor-box__output-val">Estimated clearing price range + positional surplus / deficit framing per team</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 08: CROSS-STACK ===== -->
      <section class="about-section">
        <div class="about-section-header">
          <span class="about-section-num">08</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="about-section-title">Cross-Stack Fluency</h2>
            <p class="about-section-sub">The project required operating across every discipline simultaneously — and treating none of them as someone else's problem</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="about-prose">
          <p>
            Most product builders specialize. Design-first PMs defer to engineering on architecture.
            Engineering-first PMs defer to design on systems. Business-first PMs defer to both.
            This project had no one to defer to — every layer had to be owned, which meant
            every discipline had to be fluent enough to make real decisions in.
          </p>
          <p>
            The result is a system where the design tokens inform the data model, the data model
            informs the AI context window, the AI context window informs the editorial changelog,
            and the changelog informs what gets built next. These aren't silos. They're a single
            system expressed across different disciplines.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="about-crossstack-grid">
          <div class="about-cs-card">
            <div class="about-cs-card__discipline">Design System Tokens</div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__evidence">
              A complete editorial design language built from scratch — typography scale, CSS custom
              properties with fallbacks, layered shadow tokens, component pattern catalog. The same
              token layer powers both leagues without duplication.
            </div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__artifact">tokens.css · design-system.astro</div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-cs-card">
            <div class="about-cs-card__discipline">Content Modeling</div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__evidence">
              The What's New system is a typed JSON schema with category taxonomy, screenshot
              requirements, editorial voice mandates, and a weekly rollup pipeline via GitHub Actions.
              Not a list of features — a structured content model.
            </div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__artifact">whats-new.json · weekly-changelog-rollup.mjs</div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-cs-card">
            <div class="about-cs-card__discipline">Front-End Architecture</div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__evidence">
              Astro + TypeScript with static generation, a composable component library (PlayerCell,
              PlayerDetailsModal, TradeBuilder), scoped styles, and dual-league support sharing one
              codebase without branching logic polluting every file.
            </div>
            <div class="about-cs-card__artifact">TheLeagueLayout · league-context.ts</div>
          </div>

          <div class="about-cs-card">
